      "instructions": "Find the smallest prime p such that there exists an integer n where n^4 + 1 is divisible by p. Note that for n^4 + 1 = 0 mod p to have a solution, p must be 2 or a prime of the form 8k + 1. Test primes in increasing order (2, 17, 41, 73, 89, 97, 113, ...) and for each prime, check if there is an n such that n^4 + 1 is divisible by p^2."
    },
    {
      "label": "root_finder",
      "instructions": "Once the smallest prime p is identified by the prime_searcher, find all integers m in the range 0 to p^2 - 1 such that m^4 + 1 is congruent to 0 modulo p^2. From these solutions, identify the smallest positive integer m."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent will take the prime p from the prime_searcher and the smallest integer m from the root_finder to provide the final answer in the required format."
}

